<br>
The absolute number 1 criteria for a debate is HONESTY.  If you tell a single lie, no matter how small, the entire debate becomes a worthless waste of time.  This is usually when it turns into an arguement, and not only are you wasting time but you are going backwards in hostility.<br>
<br>
Both parties must have an open mind, both to other's views and to themselves.  There are a lot of &quot;why's&quot; and &quot;because's&quot; to our views that we don't readily admit to having because we are either ashamed of the reason, or (and much more often the case) we feel the reason is detrimental to our chosen side.  If you stifle these reasons then you will never understand the other side, and you become stubborn on top of wasting time.<br>
<br>
If you can list out the reasons why you feel a certain way, negate those factors with something else, and you still have that feeling tugging at you saying that you should still think this way, then you haven't thought about all of the TRUE reasons you really feel that way.<br>
<br>
Some people say personal bias is bad for debating, but it isn't.  It is very important that you make any bias known, and make known the REAL reasons you have that bias.<br>
<br>
